Civil rights organization issues travel warning to Missouri
The national NAACP organization, which advocates civil rights for African Americans, has issued a travel warning for Missouri. The reason is the state's discriminatory practices and the racist attacks that took place there.
"NAACP's travel bulletin for Missouri will enter into force on 28 August 2017 and calls on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay special attention to special attention and to exercise extreme caution when travelling in a state of recent number of questionable racial events," the organization said in a statement.
The law, which recently came into force in Missouri, makes it difficult to export discrimination cases to court. In addition, the implementation of state laws is disproportionately directed at minorities. According to the NAACP, these factors led to the issue of a travel warning.
“Human civil rights are violated.
They will be stopped based on skin color and abused or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
"We have never heard of as many cases in a short time before."
The Missouri travel bulletin is the organization's first warning to the United States.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri as well as the death of 28-year-old Black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. He was arrested by Missouri police even though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel statement also referred to a Missouri Attorney General's report that police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than white.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be wary of their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare, for example, by including money to pay bail or tell relatives they're going to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, in 2015, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri, the sixteenth largest of the U.S. states.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The ACLU, which defends civil rights guaranteed by the constitution, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they approved immigration laws obliging the police to arrest people for immigration violations. According to the organization, this will increase racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the Ministry for Foreign Affairs, and apply to other states. Recently, however, NGOs have published them in response to specific laws and trends in the United States.
