Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares to the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease of about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes stomach cramps, swelling, repeated or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, Washington University researchers found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen bowel tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the head of the study, immune cells guard the swamp and ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Inflammation-causing cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If balance drops too close to inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome may result.
The experiments found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines.
This bacter needs tryptophan to start developing immune cells. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We experienced a link between the development of Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reutter is part of a normal intestinal microbiota," Professor Colonna says.
"The more tryptophan in mice diets, the more they had such immune cells."
If the same is true in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuterial and a high-drug diet containing tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammatory sensitivity.
In researching immune cells that strengthen tolerance, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they were not present in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from another group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the intestinal microbiome of mice, i.e. the normal community of bacteria, fungus and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the brainstorming DNA of mice were examined, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteriacacters were administered to mice grown in a sterile environment without intestinal microbiota and not developed immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in fluid and transferred small amounts of liquid – without bacteria to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into tolerability-confirming cells.
When the active ingredient was cleaned of liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indoli-3 lactic acid.
When scientists doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice, the number of tolerable cells increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, cell counts dropped to half of the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance-confirming cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteriacacter cells develop in humans in the same way as mice. However, in people with irritable bowel syndrome, glucose-related genetic defects have been observed.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," Cervantes-Barragan says.
